Establish the creative contract (the "vision") for a branching interactive-fiction
gamebook based on this premise:

PREMISE:
{{ premise }}

SCOPE: "{{ scope.name }}" — the finished story will have {{ scope.hard_dilemmas }} hard
(backbone) and {{ scope.soft_dilemmas }} soft (subplot) dramatic dilemmas, a cast of
{{ scope.cast_min }}-{{ scope.cast_max }} entities, and roughly {{ scope.passages_min }}-{{ scope.passages_max }} prose passages.

Decide: genre and subgenre; the emotional tone; 2-4 themes the story explores
(phrased as tensions or questions, e.g. "duty against desire"); the intended
audience; content notes (what to embrace, what to avoid); and a point-of-view
hint (advisory — the prose stage decides finally).

Every later stage will be held to this contract, so be specific and opinionated:
"windswept, intimate, slow-burning" is a tone; "atmospheric" is not.

A vision states texture and intent, not inventory. You cannot know yet how many
suspects, motives, or subplots the structure will hold, so never promise
countable coverage ("every X carries a Y") — later stages would be held to
arithmetic no vision can see. Say what the story must FEEL like when it commits
fully; let the structural stages decide what exists.
